revision.text:
This is a '''glossary of algebraic geometry'''.

See also [[glossary of commutative algebra]], [[glossary of classical algebraic geometry]], and [[glossary of ring theory]]. For the number-theoretic applications, see [[glossary of arithmetic and Diophantine geometry]].

For simplicity, a reference to the base scheme is often omitted; i.e., a scheme will be a scheme over some fixed base scheme ''S'' and a morphism an ''S''-morphism.

{{Compact ToC|short1|sym=yes|x=[[#XYZ|XYZ]]|y=|z=|seealso=yes|refs=yes}}

==!$@==

{{glossary}}

{{term|<math>\eta</math>}}
{{defn|1=A [[generic point]]. For example, the point associated to the zero ideal for any integral affine scheme.}}

{{term|2=''F''(''n''), ''F''(''D''), ''F''<sub>''Z''</sub>}}
{{defn|no=1|1=If ''X'' is a projective scheme with [[Serre's twisting sheaf]] <math>\mathcal{O}_X(1)</math> and if ''F'' is an <math>\mathcal{O}_X</math>-module, then <math>F(n) = F \otimes_{\mathcal{O}_X} \mathcal{O}_X(n).</math>}}
{{defn|no=2|1=If ''D'' is a Cartier divisor and ''F'' is an <math>\mathcal{O}_X</math>-module (''X'' arbitrary), then <math>F(D) = F \otimes_{\mathcal{O}_X} \mathcal{O}_X(D).</math> If ''D'' is a Weil divisor and ''F'' is reflexive, then one replaces ''F''(''D'') by its reflexive hull (and call the result still ''F''(''D'').)}}
{{defn|no=3|1=If ''Z'' is a closed subscheme of ''X'', then <math>F_Z = F \otimes_{\mathcal{O}_X} \mathcal{O}_Z</math>.}}

{{term|<nowiki>|</nowiki>''D''<nowiki>|</nowiki>}}
{{defn|1=The [[complete linear system]] of a [[Weil divisor]] ''D'' on a normal complete<!-- the completeness is just to ensure a linear system is finite-dimensional --> variety ''X'' over an algebraically closed field ''k''; that is, <math>|D| = \mathbf{P}(\Gamma(X, \mathcal{O}_X(D)))</math>. There is a bijection between the set of ''k''-rational points of <nowiki>|</nowiki>''D''<nowiki>|</nowiki> and the set of effective Weil divisors on ''X'' that are linearly equivalent to ''D''.<ref>Proof: Let ''D'' be a Weil divisor on ''X''. If ''D<nowiki>'</nowiki>'' ~ ''D'', then there is a nonzero rational function ''f'' on ''X'' such that ''D'' + (''f'') <nowiki>=</nowiki> ''D<nowiki>'</nowiki>'' and then ''f'' is a section of ''O''<sub>''X''</sub>(''D'') if ''D<nowiki>'</nowiki>'' is effective. The opposite direction is similar. □</ref> The same definition is used if ''D'' is a [[Cartier divisor]] on a complete variety over ''k''.}}

{{term|[X/G]}}
{{defn|1=The [[quotient stack]] of, say, an algebraic space ''X'' by the action of a group scheme ''G''.}}

{{term|<math>X/\!/G</math>}}
{{defn|1=The [[GIT quotient]] of a scheme ''X'' by the action of a group scheme ''G''.}}

{{term|content=''L''<sup>''n''</sup>}}
{{defn|1=An ambiguous notation. It usually means an ''n''-th tensor power of ''L'' but can also mean the self-intersection number of ''L''. If <math>L = \mathcal{O}_X</math>, the structure sheaf on ''X'', then it means the direct sum of ''n'' copies of <math>\mathcal{O}_X</math>.}}

{{term|content=<math>\mathcal{O}_X(-1)</math>}}
{{defn|1=The [[tautological line bundle]]. It is the dual of [[Serre's twisting sheaf]] <math>\mathcal{O}_X(1)</math>.}}

{{term|content=<math>\mathcal{O}_X(1)</math>}}
{{defn|1=[[Serre's twisting sheaf]]. It is the dual of the [[tautological line bundle]] <math>\mathcal{O}_X(-1)</math>. It is also called the hyperplane bundle.}}

{{term|content=<math>\mathcal{O}_X(D)</math>}}
{{defn|no=1|If ''D'' is an [[effective Cartier divisor]] on ''X'', then it is the inverse of the ideal sheaf of ''D''.}}
{{defn|no=2|Most of the times, <math>\mathcal{O}_X(D)</math> is the image of ''D'' under the natural group homomorphism from the group of Cartier divisors to the Picard group <math>\operatorname{Pic}(X)</math> of ''X'', the group of isomorphism classes of line bundles on ''X''.}}
{{defn|no=3|In general, <math>\mathcal{O}_X(D)</math> is the sheaf corresponding to a [[Weil divisor]] ''D'' (on a [[normal scheme]]). It need not be locally free, only [[reflexive sheaf|reflexive]].}}
{{defn|no=4|If ''D'' is a ℚ-divisor, then <math>\mathcal{O}_X(D)</math> is <math>\mathcal{O}_X</math> of the integral part of ''D''.}}

{{term|content=<math>\Omega_X^p</math>}}
{{defn|no=1|<math>\Omega_X^1</math> is the sheaf of [[Kähler differentials]] on ''X''.}}
{{defn|no=2|<math>\Omega_X^p</math> is the ''p''-th exterior power of <math>\Omega_X^1</math>.}}

{{term|content=<math>\Omega_X^p(\log D)</math>}}
{{defn|no=1|If ''p'' is 1, this is the sheaf of [[logarithmic Kähler differential]]s on ''X'' along ''D'' (roughly differential forms with simple poles along a divisor ''D''.)}}
{{defn|no=2|<math>\Omega_X^p(\log D)</math> is the ''p''-th exterior power of <math>\Omega_X^1(\log D)</math>.}}

{{term|'''P'''(''V'')}}
{{defn|1=Unfortunately, the notation is ambiguous. Its traditional meaning is the [[projectivization]] of a finite-dimensional ''k''-vector space ''V''; i.e.,
:<math>\mathbf{P}(V) = \operatorname{Proj}(k[V]) = \operatorname{Proj}(\operatorname{Sym}(V^*))</math>
(the [[Proj construction|Proj]] of the [[ring of polynomial functions]] ''k''[''V'']) and its ''k''-points correspond to lines in ''V''. In contrast, Hartshorne and EGA write '''P'''(''V'') for the Proj of the symmetric algebra of ''V''.}}

{{term|Q-factorial}}
{{defn|1=A normal variety is <math>\mathbb{Q}</math>-factorial if every <math>\mathbb{Q}</math>-Weil divisor is <math>\mathbb{Q}</math>-Cartier.}}

{{term|Spec(''R'')}}
{{defn|1=The set of all prime ideals in a ring ''R'' with Zariski topology; it is called the [[prime spectrum]] of ''R''.}}

{{term|content=Spec<sub>''X''</sub>(''F'')}}
{{defn|1=The [[relative Spec]] of the ''O''<sub>''X''</sub>-algebra ''F''. It is also denoted by '''Spec'''(''F'') or simply Spec(''F'').}}

{{term|content=Spec<sup>an</sup>(''R'')}}
{{defn|1=The set of all valuations for a ring ''R'' with a certain weak topology; it is called the [[Berkovich spectrum]] of ''R''.}}

{{glossary end}}

==A==

{{glossary}}
{{term|1=abelian}}
{{defn|no=1|An [[abelian variety]] is a complete group variety. For example, consider the complex variety <math>\mathbb{C}^n/\mathbb{Z}^{2n} </math> or an elliptic curve <math>E</math> over a finite field <math>\mathbb{F}_q</math>.}}
{{defn|no=2|An [[abelian scheme]] is a (flat) family of abelian varieties.}}

{{term|1=adjunction formula}}
{{defn|no=1|If ''D'' is an effective Cartier divisor on an algebraic variety ''X'', both admitting [[dualizing sheaf|dualizing sheaves]] <math>\omega_D, \omega_X</math><!-- meaning Cohen-Macaulay -->, then the [[adjunction formula]] says:
:<math>\omega_D = (\omega_X \otimes \mathcal{O}_X(D))|_D</math>.}}
{{defn|no=2|If, in addition, ''X'' and ''D'' are smooth, then the formula is equivalent to saying:
::<math>K_D = (K_X + D)|_D</math>
:where <math>K_D, K_X</math> are [[canonical divisor]]s on ''D'' and ''X''.}}

{{term|affine}}
{{defn|no=1|[[Affine space]] is roughly a vector space where one has forgotten which point is the origin}} 
{{defn|no=2|An [[affine variety]] is a variety in affine space}}
{{defn|no=3|An [[affine scheme]] is a scheme that is the [[prime spectrum]] of some commutative ring.}}
{{defn|no=4|1=
A morphism is called '''[[affine morphism|affine]]''' if the preimage of any open affine subset is again affine. In more fancy terms, affine morphisms are defined by the [[global Spec|global '''Spec''']] construction for sheaves of ''O<sub>X</sub>''-Algebras, defined by analogy with the [[spectrum of a ring]]. Important affine morphisms are [[vector bundle]]s, and [[finite morphism]]s.
}}
{{defn|no=5|The [[affine cone]] over a closed subvariety ''X'' of a projective space is the Spec of the homogeneous coordinate ring of ''X''.}}

{{quote box
|align = right
|width=33%
|quote=Algebraic geometry occupied a central place in the mathematics of the last century. The deepest results of Abel, Riemann, Weierstrass, many of the most important papers of Klein and Poincare belong to this domain. At the end of the last and the beginning of the present century the attitude towards algebraic geometry changed abruptly. ... The style of thinking that was fully developed in algebraic geometry at that time was too far removed from the set-theoretical and axiomatic spirit, which then determined the development of mathematics. ... Around the middle of the present century algebraic geometry had undergone to a large extent such a reshaping process. As a result, it can again lay claim to the position it once occupied in mathematics.
|source=From the preface to I.R. Shafarevich, Basic Algebraic Geometry.}} 
{{term|1=algebraic geometry}}
{{defn|1=[[Algebraic geometry]] is a branch of mathematics that studies solutions to algebraic equations.}}

{{term|1=algebraic geometry over the field with one element}}
{{defn|1=One goal is to prove the [[Riemann hypothesis]].<ref>{{Cite arxiv|title = An essay on the Riemann Hypothesis|arxiv = 1509.05576|journal = |date = 2015-09-18|first = Connes|last = Alain}}</ref> See also the [[field with one element]] and {{Cite arXiv|title = Mapping F_1-land:An overview of geometries over the field with one element|eprint=0909.0069 |date = 2009-08-31|first = Javier López|last = Peña|first2 = Oliver|last2 = Lorscheid}} as well as <ref>{{Cite arXiv|title = Remarks on zeta functions and K-theory over F1|eprint=math/0605429 |date = 2006-05-16|first = Anton|last = Deitmar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite arXiv|title = Homological Algebra for Commutative Monoids|eprint=1503.02309 |date = 2015-03-08|first = Jaret|last = Flores}}</ref>
.}}

{{term|1=algebraic group}}
{{defn|1=An [[algebraic group]] is an algebraic variety that is also a [[group (mathematics)|group]] in such a way the group operations are morphisms of varieties.}}

{{term|1=algebraic scheme}}
{{defn|1=A separated scheme of finite type over a field. For example, an algebraic variety is a reduced irreducible algebraic scheme.}}

{{term|1=algebraic set}}
{{defn|1=An [[algebraic set]] over a field ''k'' is a reduced separated scheme of finite type over <math>\operatorname{Spec}(k)</math>. An irreducible algebraic set is called an algebraic variety.}}

{{term|1=algebraic space}}
{{defn|1=An [[algebraic space]] is a quotient of a scheme by the [[étale equivalence relation]].}}

{{term|1=algebraic variety}}
{{defn|1=An [[algebraic variety]] over a field ''k'' is an integral separated scheme of finite type over <math>\operatorname{Spec}(k)</math>. Note, not assuming ''k'' is algebraically closed causes some pathology; for example, <math>\operatorname{Spec} \mathbb{C} \times_{\mathbb{R}} \operatorname{Spec} \mathbb{C}</math> is not a variety since the coordinate ring <math>\mathbb{C} \otimes_{\mathbb{R}} \mathbb{C}</math> is not an [[integral domain]].}}

{{term|1=algebraic vector bundle}}
{{defn|1=A [[locally free sheaf]] of a finite rank.}}

{{term|1=ample}}
{{defn|1=A line bundle on a projective variety is [[ample line bundle|ample]] if some tensor power of it is very ample.}}

{{term|1=Arakelov geometry}}
{{defn|1=Algebraic geometry over the compactification of Spec of the [[ring of rational integers]] ℤ.. See [[Arakelov geometry]].<ref>{{Cite arXiv|title = New Approach to Arakelov Geometry|eprint=0704.2030 |date = 2007-04-16|first = Nikolai|last = Durov}}</ref>}}

{{term|1=arithmetic genus}}
{{defn|1=The [[arithmetic genus]] of a projective variety ''X'' of dimension ''r'' is <math>(-1)^r (\chi(\mathcal{O}_X) - 1)</math>.}}
<!--{{term|1=arithmetic}}
{{defn|1=The [[arithmetic scheme]] is a scheme over <math>\operatorname{Spec}(\mathbf{Z})</math>, the prime spectrum of the ring of rational integers.}} but any scheme is a scheme over Spec('''Z''').-->

{{term|1=Artin stack}}
{{defn|1=Another term for an [[algebraic stack]].}}

{{term|1=artinian}}
{{defn|1=0-dimensional and Noetherian. The definition applies both to a scheme and a ring.}}

