|align = right
|width=33%
|quote=On Grothendieck’s own view there should be almost no history of schemes, but only a history of the resistance to them: ... There is no serious historical question of how Grothendieck found his definition of schemes. It was in the air. Serre has well said that no one invented schemes (conversation 1995). The question is, what made Grothendieck believe he should use this definition to simplify an 80 page paper by Serre into some 1000 pages of ''[[Éléments de géométrie algébrique]]''?
|source=[http://www.landsburg.com/grothendieck/mclarty1.pdf]
}}{{term|1=scheme}}
{{defn|1=A [[scheme (mathematics)|scheme]] is a [[locally ringed space]] that is locally a [[prime spectrum]] of a [[commutative ring]].}}

{{term|1=Schubert}}
{{defn|no=1|1=A [[Schubert cell]] is a ''B''-orbit on the Grassmannian <math>\operatorname{Gr}(d, n)</math> where ''B'' is the standard Borel; i.e., the group of upper triangular matrices.}}
{{defn|no=2|1=A [[Schubert variety]] is the closure of a Schubert cell.}}

{{term|1=secant variety}}
{{defn|1=The [[secant variety]] to a projective variety <math>V \subset \mathbb{P}^r</math> is the closure of the union of all secant lines to ''V'' in <math>\mathbb{P}^r</math>.}}

{{term|1=section ring}}
{{defn|1=The [[section ring]] or the ring of sections of a line bundle ''L'' on a scheme ''X'' is the graded ring <math>\oplus_0^\infty \Gamma(X, L^n)</math>.}}

{{term|content=Serre's conditions ''S''<sub>''n''</sub>}}
{{defn|1=See [[Serre's conditions on normality]]. See also http://mathoverflow.net/questions/22228/what-is-serres-condition-s-n-for-sheaves}}

{{term|1=Serre duality}}
{{defn|1=See [[#dualizing sheaf]]}}

{{term|1=separated}}
{{defn|1=
A separated morphism is a morphism <math> f </math> such that the [[fiber product]] of <math> f </math> with itself along <math> f </math> has its [[diagonal]] as a closed subscheme &mdash; in other words, the diagonal map is a ''closed immersion''.

As a consequence, a scheme <math> X </math> is '''separated''' when the diagonal of <math> X </math> within the ''scheme product'' of <math> X </math> with itself is a closed immersion. Emphasizing the relative point of view, one might equivalently define a scheme to be separated if the unique morphism <math>X \rightarrow \textrm{Spec} (\mathbb{Z})</math> is separated.

Notice that a [[topological space]] ''Y'' is Hausdorff iff the diagonal embedding 
:<math>Y \stackrel{\Delta}{\longrightarrow} Y \times Y</math>
is closed. In algebraic geometry, the above formulation is used because a scheme which is a Hausdorff space is necessarily empty or zero-dimensional. The difference between the topological and algebro-geometric context comes from the topological structure of the fiber product (in the category of schemes) <math>X \times_{\textrm{Spec} (\mathbb{Z})} X</math>, which is different from the product of topological spaces.

Any ''affine'' scheme ''Spec A'' is separated, because the diagonal corresponds to the surjective map of rings (hence is a closed immersion of schemes):
:''<math>A \otimes_{\mathbb Z} A \rightarrow A, a \otimes a' \mapsto a \cdot a'</math>''.
}}

{{term|1=sheaf generated by global sections}}
{{defn|1=A sheaf with a set of global sections that span the stalk of the sheaf at every point. See [[Sheaf generated by global sections]].}}

{{term|1=simple}}
{{defn|1=The term "simple point" is an old term for a "smooth point".}}

{{term|1=smooth}}
{{defn|no=1|1=
{{main|smooth morphism}}
The higher-dimensional analog of étale morphisms are ''smooth morphisms''.  There are many different characterisations of smoothness. The following are equivalent definitions of smoothness of the morphism {{nowrap|''f'' : ''Y'' → ''X''}}:
:1) for any ''y'' &isin; ''Y'', there are open affine neighborhoods ''V'' and ''U'' of ''y'', ''x''=''f''(''y''), respectively, such that the restriction of ''f'' to ''V'' factors as an étale morphism followed by the projection of [[affine space|affine ''n''-space]] over ''U''.
:2) ''f'' is flat, locally of finite presentation, and for every geometric point <math>\bar{y}</math> of ''Y'' (a morphism from the spectrum of an algebraically closed field <math>k(\bar{y})</math> to ''Y''), the geometric fiber <math>X_{\bar{y}}:=X\times_Y \mathrm{Spec} (k(\bar{y}))</math> is a smooth ''n''-dimensional variety over <math>k(\bar{y})</math> in the sense of classical algebraic geometry.
}}
{{defn|no=2|1=A [[smooth scheme]] over a perfect field ''k'' is a scheme ''X'' that is of locally of finite type and [[regular scheme|regular]] over ''k''.}}
{{defn|no=3|1=A smooth scheme over a field ''k'' is a scheme ''X'' that is geometrically smooth: <math>X \times_k \overline{k}</math> is smooth.}}

{{term|1=special}}
{{defn|1=A divisor ''D'' on a smooth curve ''C'' is [[special divsor|special]] if <math>h^0(\mathcal{O}(K - D))</math>, which is called the index of speciality, is positive.}}

{{term|1=spherical variety}}
{{defn|1=A [[spherical variety]] is a normal ''G''-variety (''G'' connected reductive) with an open dense orbit by a Borel subgroup of ''G''.}}

{{term|1=stable}}
{{defn|no=1|A [[stable curve]] is a curve with some "mild" singularity, used to construct a good-behaving [[moduli space of curves]].}}
{{defn|no=2|A [[stable vector bundle]] is used to construct the [[moduli space of vector bundles]].}}

{{term|1=stack}}
{{defn|1=A [[stack (mathematics)|stack]] parametrizes sets of points together with automorphisms.}}

{{term|1=strict transform}}
{{defn|1=Given a blow-up <math>\pi: \widetilde{X} \to X</math> along a closed subscheme ''Z'' and a morphism <math>f: Y \to X</math>, the [[strict transform]] of ''Y'' (also called proper transform) is the blow-up <math>\widetilde{Y} \to Y</math> of ''Y'' along the closed subscheme <math>f^{-1} Z</math>. If ''f'' is a closed immersion, then the induced map <math>\widetilde{Y} \hookrightarrow \widetilde{X}</math> is also a closed immersion.}}

{{term|1=subscheme}}
{{defn|1=
A '''subscheme''', without qualifier, of ''X'' is a closed subscheme of an open subscheme of ''X''.
}}

{{term|1=surface}}
{{defn|1=An algebraic variety of dimension two.}}

{{term|1=symmetric variety}}
{{defn|1=An analog of a [[symmetric space]]. See [[symmetric variety]].}}

