'''William Wade Dunham''' (born 1947) is an American [[scientific writing|writer]] who was originally trained in [[topology]] but became interested in the [[history of mathematics]] and specializes in [[Leonhard Euler]]. He has received several awards for writing and teaching on this subject.<ref name=passhema> {{cite web |url=http://www.passhema.org/past-conferences/2002/sshema/Dunham2.html |title=William Dunham |publisher=www.passhema.org |accessdate=2008-06-15}}</ref>
==Education== Dunham received his [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] from the [[University of Pittsburgh]] in 1969, his [[Master of Science|M.S.]] from [[Ohio State]] in 1970, and his [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] from the same institution in 1974.
==Writings== Dunham won the American Association of Publishers’ award for writing the Best Mathematics Book of 1994 for his book '' The Mathematical Universe''.<ref name=passhema/> In his book ''Euler: The Master of Us All'', he examines Leonhard Euler's impressive mathematical work.<ref> {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&id=uKOVNvGOkhQC&dq=William+Dunham&printsec=frontcover&source=web&ots=K1Yeq-szNv&sig=JMKQfYXjA-2d7hhlbmYphgmqh7s&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=2&ct=result |title=Euler: The Master of Us All - Google Book Search |publisher=books.google.com |accessdate=2008-06-15 |last=Dunham |first=Willam }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Wagner, Clifford|title=Review of ''Euler: The Master of Us All'' by William Dunham|website=Mathematical Association of America|date=July 2007|url=http://www.maa.org/publications/periodicals/convergence/euler-the-master-of-us-all}}</ref> He received a [[Lester R. Ford Award]] in 2006 for his expository article ''Touring the Calculus''.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Dunham, William|title=Touring the Calculus|journal=Amer. Math. Monthly|year=2005|volume=112|pages=1–19|url=http://www.maa.org/programs/maa-awards/writing-awards/touring-the-calculus-gallery|doi=10.2307/30037380}}</ref>
In 2007, Dunham gave a lecture about Euler's product-sum formula and its relationship to [[analytic number theory]], as well as discussed Euler's evaluation of a non-trivial integral at the celebration of "Year of Euler" by the [[Euler Society]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maa.org/news/070907mfhighlight.html |title=MathFest Highlight: William Dunham Presents Euler in Three Acts |publisher=www.maa.org |accessdate=2008-06-15}}</ref> He published a chapter "Euler and the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra" in the book ''The Genius of Euler'' published in 2007 to commemorate the 300th birthday of Euler.<ref> {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&id=M4-zUnrSxNoC&dq=William+Dunham&printsec=frontcover&source=web&ots=9D0NCh4T2R&sig=aQvYIsJtoRcOpLth-cBATCZdKnU&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=10&ct=result |title=The genius of Euler: reflections on ... - Google Book Search |publisher=books.google.com |accessdate=2008-06-15 |last=Dunham |first=William }} </ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Bradley, Rob|date=25 February 2007|website=Mathematical Association of America|title=Review of ''The Genius of Euler'' edited by William Dunham|url=http://www.maa.org/publications/maa-reviews/the-genius-of-euler-reflections-on-his-life-and-work}}</ref>
